00:00:25.398 --> 00:00:28.740 align:middle line:10%
>> If you're one of the 90%
of Americans who have suffered

00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:32.159 align:middle line:10%
from back pain, you know just
how frustrating it can be.

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:35.490 align:middle line:84%
Healer Esther Gokhale believes
that back pain is largely

00:00:35.490 --> 00:00:38.040 align:middle line:90%
the result of improper posture.

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:42.120 align:middle line:84%
She's the founder of the Gokhale
Method, a revolutionary program

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:44.400 align:middle line:84%
that teaches people how
to use healthy posture

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:47.820 align:middle line:84%
and movement to restore
their structural integrity

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:49.680 align:middle line:90%
and banish pain.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:52.680 align:middle line:84%
Esther is the author
of bestseller "8 Steps

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:55.890 align:middle line:84%
to a Pain-Free Back," and
has been dubbed the posture

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.780 align:middle line:90%
guru of Silicon Valley.

00:00:58.780 --> 00:01:01.030 align:middle line:84%
Esther, welcome
to Healing Matrix.

00:01:01.030 --> 00:01:02.290 align:middle line:90%
>> Delighted to be here.

00:01:02.290 --> 00:01:03.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, wonderful.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:05.870 align:middle line:84%
Just tell us a little bit
about your background.

00:01:05.870 --> 00:01:09.400 align:middle line:84%
How did you get interested
in healing in particular?

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:11.500 align:middle line:90%
>> Healing because of my mother.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:14.620 align:middle line:84%
She was a registered
nurse from Holland.

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:16.990 align:middle line:10%
Married my father, an Indian.

00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:20.380 align:middle line:10%
And while she was
in India, she took

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:23.350 align:middle line:10%
care of sick orphans,
abandoned babies,

00:01:23.350 --> 00:01:25.090 align:middle line:10%
nursed them back to health.

00:01:25.090 --> 00:01:27.160 align:middle line:84%
And I saw some
pretty amazing things

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:30.550 align:middle line:84%
happen, and was very
impressed and inspired

00:01:30.550 --> 00:01:34.030 align:middle line:84%
that unusual methods
could have an impact.

00:01:34.030 --> 00:01:38.240 align:middle line:10%
>> And did you have a particular
personal interest in back pain

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:39.040 align:middle line:10%
in particular?

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:43.130 align:middle line:10%
>> Well, I came to it the hard
way with my own very severe

00:01:43.130 --> 00:01:43.930 align:middle line:10%
problems.

00:01:43.930 --> 00:01:48.160 align:middle line:84%
I had a L5-S1 herniated
disc when I was

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:50.510 align:middle line:90%
pregnant with my first child.

00:01:50.510 --> 00:01:54.010 align:middle line:84%
And I was trying all
the usual conservative

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:58.470 align:middle line:84%
and alternative approaches
and not getting anywhere.

00:01:58.470 --> 00:02:01.450 align:middle line:84%
And eventually, I
had to have surgery.

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:05.140 align:middle line:84%
At that point, it was a huge
herniation and two fragments

00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:07.420 align:middle line:90%
floating around in the canal.

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:10.539 align:middle line:90%
And so that helped.

00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:14.890 align:middle line:84%
But then a year later, I
re-herniated the same disc.

00:02:14.890 --> 00:02:21.250 align:middle line:84%
And so that surgery hadn't
lasted as a result either.

00:02:21.250 --> 00:02:26.290 align:middle line:84%
And so I was forced to
cast my net wider and look

00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:27.940 align:middle line:84%
for something that
would help me.

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:28.750 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:31.870 align:middle line:84%
And then you traveled to
Paris and something unfolded.

00:02:31.870 --> 00:02:33.460 align:middle line:90%
>> I did.

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:36.940 align:middle line:84%
The approaches that
resonated for me

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:42.250 align:middle line:84%
were the ones that point
you to your own body

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:43.660 align:middle line:90%
and the way you're using it.

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:48.310 align:middle line:84%
And that included Alexander
Technique, and Feldenkrais,

00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:50.890 align:middle line:84%
and Aplomb, which is
a French technique.

00:02:50.890 --> 00:02:55.180 align:middle line:84%
And I spent an
entire year in Paris

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:58.900 align:middle line:84%
and then several more
years in close association

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:00.970 align:middle line:90%
with the Aplomb teachers.

00:03:00.970 --> 00:03:06.100 align:middle line:84%
And they were pointing to
indigenous people and ancestral

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:07.060 align:middle line:90%
populations.

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:08.800 align:middle line:90%
And that made sense to me.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:10.930 align:middle line:84%
When I was growing up
in India, my mother

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:15.550 align:middle line:84%
would always point out to the
sweeper and the fruit seller

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:18.640 align:middle line:84%
and point out how amazing
they were in the way they

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:19.690 align:middle line:90%
used their bodies.

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:25.200 align:middle line:84%
So anything that was
pointing to indigenous,

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:29.580 align:middle line:84%
primal ways of using
your own body resonated.

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.850 align:middle line:84%
And so I was diving into
the medical literature

00:03:32.850 --> 00:03:36.930 align:middle line:84%
to see if indeed there
were populations that had

00:03:36.930 --> 00:03:38.550 align:middle line:90%
lower incidence of back pain.

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:43.260 align:middle line:84%
And then I started traveling
and filming and photographing

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:47.730 align:middle line:84%
things I observed, interviewing
people, and discovering

00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:49.830 align:middle line:84%
that it really is
true that there

00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:53.910 align:middle line:84%
are populations that have a much
lower incidence of back pain.

00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:58.770 align:middle line:84%
And they sit differently, walk
differently, bend differently,

00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:02.040 align:middle line:84%
even lie down differently
than we in the modern west do.

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:05.950 align:middle line:84%
>> We have video of Esther
in Burkina Faso, Africa.

00:04:05.950 --> 00:04:08.150 align:middle line:84%
Esther, tell us about
what we're seeing here.

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:12.180 align:middle line:84%
>> So I am mimicking
this group of women,

00:04:12.180 --> 00:04:15.780 align:middle line:84%
who are walking with
weight on their heads.

00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:19.620 align:middle line:10%
And one of the things to observe
is how they use their glutes

00:04:19.620 --> 00:04:22.200 align:middle line:10%
to propel themselves forward.

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:27.840 align:middle line:84%
Every step is a rep for their
gluteus maximus and gluteus

00:04:27.840 --> 00:04:29.430 align:middle line:90%
medius muscles.

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:32.770 align:middle line:84%
You see how their behinds
are out behind them?

00:04:32.770 --> 00:04:36.240 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out
that mimicking people

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:40.080 align:middle line:84%
who know what they're doing is
a particularly fantastic way

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:41.940 align:middle line:90%
of learning posture.

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:46.160 align:middle line:84%
Unfortunately,
we're copying what's

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:48.840 align:middle line:84%
around us, which is not
such wonderful posture.

00:04:48.840 --> 00:04:49.640 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:51.650 align:middle line:84%
Most people today
slump and slouch.

00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:55.190 align:middle line:84%
And we, whether we like it or
not, whether we know it or not,

00:04:55.190 --> 00:04:57.220 align:middle line:90%
are copying what's around.

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:00.670 align:middle line:84%
So having examples
of good posture

00:05:00.670 --> 00:05:02.360 align:middle line:90%
is just extremely helpful.

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:05.180 align:middle line:84%
>> What were some of the
most profound observations

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:08.510 align:middle line:84%
and conclusions that you've
drawn from your worldwide

00:05:08.510 --> 00:05:10.026 align:middle line:90%
research?

00:05:10.026 --> 00:05:14.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, one is that the
basic shape of the spine

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:18.830 align:middle line:84%
in populations where they don't
have so much back pain and hip

00:05:18.830 --> 00:05:23.570 align:middle line:84%
arthritis and plantar fasciitis
and a host of musculoskeletal

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:28.760 align:middle line:84%
problems is that they have what
I call a J spine rather than

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:32.960 align:middle line:84%
an S spine, which is what
conventional wisdom describes

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:35.850 align:middle line:90%
as normal for our species.

00:05:35.850 --> 00:05:41.540 align:middle line:84%
So the J is like a modern
J. Its like a hockey stick,

00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:45.320 align:middle line:84%
where the behind is
distinctly behind.

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:48.290 align:middle line:84%
And then up above,
you don't have so much

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:52.010 align:middle line:84%
of what's considered
a normal lumbar curve.

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:54.560 align:middle line:84%
That portion of the
back in these people

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:57.960 align:middle line:84%
is relatively
straight up and down.

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:00.650 align:middle line:90%
So J spine rather than S spine.

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:05.210 align:middle line:84%
And that is preserved
in sitting, in standing,

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:07.010 align:middle line:90%
in walking.

00:06:07.010 --> 00:06:10.490 align:middle line:84%
And it has a host
of implications.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:14.420 align:middle line:84%
If your behind is behind, then
the glutes are in a position

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:19.130 align:middle line:84%
to work, as we saw
in the video clip.

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:25.010 align:middle line:84%
The glutes can propel the person
forward and tone themselves,

00:06:25.010 --> 00:06:28.430 align:middle line:84%
so now there's not the
need to go to a gym

00:06:28.430 --> 00:06:32.310 align:middle line:84%
and do all of these reps and
push weights around and so on.

00:06:32.310 --> 00:06:35.990 align:middle line:84%
These people are
exercising all day long.

00:06:35.990 --> 00:06:39.890 align:middle line:84%
>> Many people also say that
our sedentary lifestyle,

00:06:39.890 --> 00:06:43.370 align:middle line:84%
becoming computerized and
sitting down and all this,

00:06:43.370 --> 00:06:45.590 align:middle line:90%
is a contributor to back pain.

00:06:45.590 --> 00:06:47.252 align:middle line:90%
What's your take on that?

00:06:47.252 --> 00:06:50.110 align:middle line:84%
>> So I think sitting
has been much maligned.

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:53.495 align:middle line:84%
If you go back a few decades,
standing was the bad guy.

00:06:53.495 --> 00:06:58.270 align:middle line:84%
You know, people in assembly
lines getting varicose veins.

00:06:58.270 --> 00:06:59.330 align:middle line:90%
And that's still true.

00:06:59.330 --> 00:07:01.900 align:middle line:84%
People who stand all day
have an increased risk

00:07:01.900 --> 00:07:04.580 align:middle line:90%
of atherosclerosis.

00:07:04.580 --> 00:07:07.110 align:middle line:84%
Your fine motor
skills are less good.

00:07:07.110 --> 00:07:08.860 align:middle line:84%
There are certain
kinds of focused

00:07:08.860 --> 00:07:12.040 align:middle line:84%
thinking that don't happen
as well when you're standing.

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:13.810 align:middle line:84%
So there's a
downside to standing.

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:15.100 align:middle line:90%
We used to be aware of it.

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:16.960 align:middle line:90%
Now the fashions have changed.

00:07:16.960 --> 00:07:18.052 align:middle line:90%
Sitting's the bad guy.

00:07:18.052 --> 00:07:19.510 align:middle line:84%
I don't think either
is reasonable.

00:07:19.510 --> 00:07:20.930 align:middle line:90%
>> It's always something, right?

00:07:20.930 --> 00:07:23.960 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, it makes
for good headlines.

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:24.760 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:26.810 align:middle line:90%
Sitting is the new smoking.

00:07:26.810 --> 00:07:32.700 align:middle line:84%
But if you really examine
the data, people who sit

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:34.950 align:middle line:84%
do better than
people who are doing

00:07:34.950 --> 00:07:37.170 align:middle line:90%
manual labor in our society.

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:39.270 align:middle line:84%
You have to earn
your living some way.

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:43.290 align:middle line:84%
And the truth is that sitting
seems to actually protect you

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:45.640 align:middle line:90%
from worse stuff happening.

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:47.670 align:middle line:84%
So it's not really
fair to blame sitting.

00:07:47.670 --> 00:07:50.590 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, we all
do pretty badly.

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:54.090 align:middle line:84%
But if you look at these
non-industrial cultures,

00:07:54.090 --> 00:07:57.120 align:middle line:84%
they do well and they
are actually sitting

00:07:57.120 --> 00:07:59.075 align:middle line:90%
just about as much as we do.

00:07:59.075 --> 00:08:00.150 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:03.180 align:middle line:84%
What about obesity,
stress, one's height,

00:08:03.180 --> 00:08:07.230 align:middle line:84%
those kinds of issues that
also we commonly hear people

00:08:07.230 --> 00:08:09.330 align:middle line:84%
say, well, of course
I've got this bad back.

00:08:09.330 --> 00:08:11.832 align:middle line:84%
I'm this tall and I'm
always trying to--

00:08:11.832 --> 00:08:13.040 align:middle line:90%
you know, this kind of thing?

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:13.860 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:08:13.860 --> 00:08:17.010 align:middle line:84%
So I look at it a little bit
like you look at construction.

00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:19.380 align:middle line:84%
If you have a
skyscraper, you know,

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:23.470 align:middle line:84%
a little bit taller, if it's
well aligned, is not a problem.

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:26.400 align:middle line:84%
If it's a little broader,
and it's well aligned,

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:27.300 align:middle line:90%
not a problem.

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:29.580 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's similar
with human beings.

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:33.809 align:middle line:84%
If we were well aligned, there's
not a very strong correlation

00:08:33.809 --> 00:08:35.429 align:middle line:90%
with weight and height.

00:08:35.429 --> 00:08:38.880 align:middle line:84%
But if you are poorly
aligned, then every inch

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:42.419 align:middle line:84%
counts against you and every
ounce counts against you.

00:08:42.419 --> 00:08:44.880 align:middle line:84%
And so I think it's
the combination

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:50.100 align:middle line:84%
of poor structure, poor
musculoskeletal health,

00:08:50.100 --> 00:08:52.510 align:middle line:90%
and these other factors.

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:54.545 align:middle line:84%
Then everything
counts against you.

00:08:54.545 --> 00:08:56.670 align:middle line:84%
>> And of course, the
question is going to come up.

00:08:56.670 --> 00:08:59.970 align:middle line:84%
What about aging and
natural wear and tear?

00:08:59.970 --> 00:09:04.140 align:middle line:84%
You know, am I supposed to be
in pain because I'm in my 70s?

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:05.810 align:middle line:84%
Or you know, what's
the story there?

00:09:05.810 --> 00:09:09.265 align:middle line:84%
>> So I think we're designed
to last well for our natural

00:09:09.265 --> 00:09:10.065 align:middle line:90%
lives.

00:09:10.065 --> 00:09:12.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Lifetime guarantee we're
supposed to have on this body,

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:12.940 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:14.090 align:middle line:90%
It should last a lifetime.

00:09:14.090 --> 00:09:18.090 align:middle line:84%
>> But the problem is, we don't
arrive with the user's manual.

00:09:18.090 --> 00:09:23.970 align:middle line:84%
And then that causes increasing
wear and tear and degeneration.

00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:29.250 align:middle line:84%
And then like height and weight,
age becomes a problem, too.

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:37.190 align:middle line:84%
So in our courses, we have
seen 100-year-olds, babies,

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:39.080 align:middle line:90%
and everything in between.

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:43.100 align:middle line:84%
And you can always help people
improve their structure.

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:45.950 align:middle line:84%
And people are usually
very astonished at how much

00:09:45.950 --> 00:09:50.600 align:middle line:84%
of an effect that has on
their pains and aches.

00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:52.190 align:middle line:84%
Aches and pains are
like nature trying

00:09:52.190 --> 00:09:53.950 align:middle line:84%
to tell you, hey, do
something different.

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:54.867 align:middle line:90%
>> Pay attention here.

00:09:54.867 --> 00:09:56.370 align:middle line:84%
I'm trying to get
your attention.

00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:58.100 align:middle line:84%
So let's just take a
look at this image.

00:09:58.100 --> 00:10:01.216 align:middle line:84%
If you could explain to
us what we're seeing here.

00:10:01.216 --> 00:10:06.240 align:middle line:84%
>> So we're seeing an
old-fashioned French magazine

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:07.040 align:middle line:90%
cover.

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:14.230 align:middle line:84%
So this is pre-World
War I. And you

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:19.060 align:middle line:84%
see how the back of the
neck is very elongated,

00:10:19.060 --> 00:10:23.140 align:middle line:84%
the chin angles down
in the woman standing?

00:10:23.140 --> 00:10:26.170 align:middle line:84%
And her shoulders
are open and broad.

00:10:26.170 --> 00:10:29.560 align:middle line:84%
This is what is
truly good posture.

00:10:29.560 --> 00:10:32.260 align:middle line:84%
It's stylized, there's
some clothes around it.

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:35.275 align:middle line:84%
But this is what I consider
old-fashioned good posture.

00:10:35.275 --> 00:10:38.200 align:middle line:84%
>> So it's an enlongation
in the cervical spine.

00:10:38.200 --> 00:10:40.442 align:middle line:90%
>> In the neck, in the back.

00:10:40.442 --> 00:10:41.650 align:middle line:90%
And then the behind's behind.

00:10:41.650 --> 00:10:43.285 align:middle line:90%
A J spine again.

00:10:43.285 --> 00:10:44.870 align:middle line:90%
>> So the J spine.

00:10:44.870 --> 00:10:46.720 align:middle line:90%
So this is what it looks like.

00:10:46.720 --> 00:10:50.710 align:middle line:84%
And then an alternative posture
that we've gotten into trouble

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:51.940 align:middle line:90%
with after World War--

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:53.900 align:middle line:90%
>> I, roughly.

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:56.200 align:middle line:84%
>> So can you speak to us
about what we're seeing here?

00:10:56.200 --> 00:11:00.160 align:middle line:84%
>> So you see in this
French magazine cover,

00:11:00.160 --> 00:11:01.790 align:middle line:90%
the newer fashion.

00:11:01.790 --> 00:11:04.510 align:middle line:84%
You see how the
pelvis is tucked,

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:07.510 align:middle line:84%
how the neck
extends forward, how

00:11:07.510 --> 00:11:11.970 align:middle line:84%
the shoulders are
protruding, and the chest

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:14.160 align:middle line:90%
becomes much more flat.

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:17.620 align:middle line:84%
It's a whole different
way of being in the body.

00:11:17.620 --> 00:11:22.910 align:middle line:84%
And this has been our
fashion ever since.

00:11:22.910 --> 00:11:27.950 align:middle line:84%
You know, this is what remains
cool on the runways today.

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:35.802 align:middle line:84%
And it's very different
and much less healthy.

00:11:35.802 --> 00:11:40.870 align:middle line:84%
>> As we are seeing these images
and you're describing this S

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:48.080 align:middle line:84%
and J relationship, can you just
again share with us the J curve

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:53.590 align:middle line:84%
and how someone can know
if they are in it or not,

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:56.230 align:middle line:84%
and as it relates to
what we're seeing here?

00:11:56.230 --> 00:12:00.220 align:middle line:10%
>> On the left, you have
the classic S-shaped spine,

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:04.480 align:middle line:10%
the S spine that you find
in every modern anatomy book

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:06.340 align:middle line:10%
and chiropractic chart.

00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:13.450 align:middle line:10%
And it is the basis for lumbar
support, lumbar pillows,

00:12:13.450 --> 00:12:17.200 align:middle line:10%
every car seat
having lumbar support

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:23.430 align:middle line:10%
to fit what is thought to
be a natural sort of curve

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:25.410 align:middle line:10%
in the small of the back.

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:28.590 align:middle line:10%
On the right, you have
a picture of the spine

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:32.050 align:middle line:10%
from an anatomy book
published in 1911.

00:12:32.050 --> 00:12:35.010 align:middle line:10%
And it shows what I'm
calling the J spine.

00:12:35.010 --> 00:12:38.600 align:middle line:10%
And you see how the behind
is very much behind.

00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:43.890 align:middle line:10%
But right above the behind,
you see that the lumbar spine

00:12:43.890 --> 00:12:46.590 align:middle line:10%
is relatively straight.

00:12:46.590 --> 00:12:52.200 align:middle line:10%
And I'm arguing that that
makes a whole lot more sense

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:55.770 align:middle line:10%
and it correlates
with back health.

00:12:55.770 --> 00:13:01.430 align:middle line:84%
And there are radiologic
studies demonstrating that.

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:06.710 align:middle line:84%
And you can use
common-sensical arguments

00:13:06.710 --> 00:13:12.890 align:middle line:84%
because in that J spine, all
the discs' cylindrical shape

00:13:12.890 --> 00:13:14.480 align:middle line:90%
is respected.

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:18.500 align:middle line:10%
And the vertebrae are
not edgewise compressed.

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:23.090 align:middle line:10%
And the wedge shape
of the L5-S1 disc,

00:13:23.090 --> 00:13:27.080 align:middle line:10%
the very lowest
disc in our spine,

00:13:27.080 --> 00:13:34.240 align:middle line:10%
that adapted to becoming
wedge-shaped as part

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:36.310 align:middle line:10%
of being bipedal.

00:13:36.310 --> 00:13:39.040 align:middle line:84%
And that wedge
shape is respected.

00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:41.500 align:middle line:90%
So you have the behind behind.

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:48.760 align:middle line:84%
And that just makes a whole
lot more sense in so many ways.

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:52.450 align:middle line:84%
>> It's very interesting for
us to be bringing this forth,

00:13:52.450 --> 00:13:54.880 align:middle line:84%
and we've been through so
many changes through this time

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:56.297 align:middle line:84%
period that you're
speaking about.

00:13:56.297 --> 00:13:59.050 align:middle line:84%
I can see the correlation about
what might be happening here.

00:13:59.050 --> 00:14:02.500 align:middle line:84%
And you have something
super exciting to share

00:14:02.500 --> 00:14:06.910 align:middle line:84%
with us that is a tool that
allows us to monitor what

00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:09.790 align:middle line:84%
the spine is doing in
real time, that can even

00:14:09.790 --> 00:14:12.790 align:middle line:84%
act as a biofeedback
type of teacher

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:16.180 align:middle line:84%
for us to see how we're
orienting ourselves

00:14:16.180 --> 00:14:19.060 align:middle line:84%
inside the body and
utilizing our spine.

00:14:19.060 --> 00:14:22.300 align:middle line:84%
So can you tell us a little
bit about this spine tracker

00:14:22.300 --> 00:14:24.400 align:middle line:90%
that you have with us today?

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:30.040 align:middle line:84%
>> So this consists of
five sensors that get stuck

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:31.220 align:middle line:90%
