00:22:04.130 --> 00:22:05.320 align:middle line:90%
>> Mm-hmm.

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:07.560 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the aid
that you do recommend.

00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:08.360 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:22:08.360 --> 00:22:11.030 align:middle line:84%
So I think aids can
be really helpful,

00:22:11.030 --> 00:22:13.250 align:middle line:84%
but they just need
to be well-informed.

00:22:13.250 --> 00:22:16.150 align:middle line:84%
They need to have the right
philosophy guiding them

00:22:16.150 --> 00:22:18.290 align:middle line:90%
and not be counterproductive.

00:22:18.290 --> 00:22:21.770 align:middle line:84%
>> Can you show us how the
Stretchsit cushion works?

00:22:21.770 --> 00:22:22.620 align:middle line:90%
>> I'd be delighted.

00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:23.420 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:22:23.420 --> 00:22:24.320 align:middle line:90%
Excellent.

00:22:24.320 --> 00:22:26.200 align:middle line:90%
Show us what's happening here.

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:31.150 align:middle line:84%
>> So the chair, as you can
see, has these sticky nubs,

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:33.880 align:middle line:90%
and that offers friction.

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:36.010 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is that
the person sitting

00:22:36.010 --> 00:22:40.060 align:middle line:84%
would lengthen their spine,
hook up against the cushion,

00:22:40.060 --> 00:22:43.410 align:middle line:84%
and then be a little taller
And basically have traction.

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:44.830 align:middle line:90%
And I'll demo.

00:22:44.830 --> 00:22:48.460 align:middle line:84%
So we teach people to put their
bum well back in the chair,

00:22:48.460 --> 00:22:51.010 align:middle line:84%
and then come away
from the sticky nubs

00:22:51.010 --> 00:22:52.780 align:middle line:90%
and then elongate their spine.

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:56.650 align:middle line:84%
First by curving
forward and that

00:22:56.650 --> 00:22:58.950 align:middle line:84%
undoes whatever extra
lumbar curve they have.

00:22:58.950 --> 00:22:59.750 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:22:59.750 --> 00:23:01.900 align:middle line:84%
>> And then grabbing either
the pillow or some part

00:23:01.900 --> 00:23:05.650 align:middle line:84%
of the chair to make
the back even taller.

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:09.490 align:middle line:84%
And then hooking the
back to the sticky nubs.

00:23:09.490 --> 00:23:13.090 align:middle line:84%
And now the back
is getting a boost

00:23:13.090 --> 00:23:18.310 align:middle line:84%
whereas previously the back
was just short and compressed

00:23:18.310 --> 00:23:20.900 align:middle line:84%
and getting all kinds
of wear and tear.

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:23.650 align:middle line:84%
So that's extremely
helpful way to make

00:23:23.650 --> 00:23:29.620 align:middle line:84%
sitting not only more
comfortable, but also more

00:23:29.620 --> 00:23:30.940 align:middle line:90%
therapeutic.

00:23:30.940 --> 00:23:32.950 align:middle line:84%
>> So rather than the
compressive forces,

00:23:32.950 --> 00:23:35.710 align:middle line:84%
you're actually tractioning
as you're seated.

00:23:35.710 --> 00:23:36.630 align:middle line:90%
>> Exactly.

00:23:36.630 --> 00:23:37.120 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:23:37.120 --> 00:23:37.920 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:39.850 align:middle line:90%
>> So beautiful combination.

00:23:39.850 --> 00:23:43.570 align:middle line:84%
So informative, traction
while you're sitting, amazing.

00:23:43.570 --> 00:23:46.990 align:middle line:84%
It brings to mind something
that many people also

00:23:46.990 --> 00:23:49.220 align:middle line:90%
have feet issues.

00:23:49.220 --> 00:23:51.190 align:middle line:84%
And oftentimes,
traction helps that.

00:23:51.190 --> 00:23:52.780 align:middle line:84%
It makes me think
about, is there

00:23:52.780 --> 00:23:56.440 align:middle line:84%
something that you can share
with us about the biomechanics

00:23:56.440 --> 00:24:01.540 align:middle line:84%
related to the spine and posture
and how it translates down

00:24:01.540 --> 00:24:03.765 align:middle line:90%
to the issue of foot pain?

00:24:03.765 --> 00:24:07.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Like the ditty goes, the
foot bone's connected to the leg

00:24:07.570 --> 00:24:10.120 align:middle line:84%
bone, and the leg bone's
connected to-- so yes.

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:13.570 align:middle line:84%
I'm definitely in the camp
of everything is connected--

00:24:13.570 --> 00:24:14.380 align:middle line:90%
>> You bet.

00:24:14.380 --> 00:24:15.850 align:middle line:90%
>> --very literally.

00:24:15.850 --> 00:24:18.310 align:middle line:84%
In particular, the
way most people

00:24:18.310 --> 00:24:23.170 align:middle line:84%
stand, they park their hips
forward and put a lot of weight

00:24:23.170 --> 00:24:25.360 align:middle line:90%
on the front of the foot.

00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:30.970 align:middle line:84%
And this is easy on all the leg
muscles which get to turn off.

00:24:30.970 --> 00:24:36.880 align:middle line:84%
But every joint,
knee, hip, spine,

00:24:36.880 --> 00:24:40.840 align:middle line:84%
is put under stress in
this way and in the foot.

00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:43.810 align:middle line:84%
So that, as well
as the way people

00:24:43.810 --> 00:24:47.800 align:middle line:84%
walk where they tend to lift
their heel way too early,

00:24:47.800 --> 00:24:52.090 align:middle line:84%
puts a lot of stress on
the front of the foot

00:24:52.090 --> 00:24:55.400 align:middle line:84%
and leads to things
like plantar fasciitis

00:24:55.400 --> 00:24:59.290 align:middle line:90%
and Morton's neuroma and all--

00:24:59.290 --> 00:25:02.950 align:middle line:84%
bunions and all sorts
of common ailments

00:25:02.950 --> 00:25:06.150 align:middle line:84%
that there really isn't
a very good way around.

00:25:06.150 --> 00:25:09.430 align:middle line:84%
Once your foot is in
trouble, now what do you do?

00:25:09.430 --> 00:25:15.330 align:middle line:84%
I've had people crawl into
my office in desperation.

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:18.540 align:middle line:84%
>> So you're recommending longer
on the heel before the heel

00:25:18.540 --> 00:25:19.340 align:middle line:90%
lift--

00:25:19.340 --> 00:25:20.140 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:25:20.140 --> 00:25:22.920 align:middle line:84%
>> --as they're moving into
the heel strike in front, yes?

00:25:22.920 --> 00:25:23.720 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:26.910 align:middle line:84%
So the heel, as you know
in our species, is huge.

00:25:26.910 --> 00:25:27.910 align:middle line:90%
It's dense.

00:25:27.910 --> 00:25:29.490 align:middle line:90%
It has cross fiber construction.

00:25:29.490 --> 00:25:30.960 align:middle line:90%
It is made for weight bearing.

00:25:30.960 --> 00:25:31.760 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:34.260 align:middle line:84%
>> And leaving the weight
there, both in standing as well

00:25:34.260 --> 00:25:39.350 align:middle line:84%
as in a prolonged way in
walking, makes a lot of sense.

00:25:39.350 --> 00:25:43.560 align:middle line:84%
And it's the way that these
indigenous people walk.

00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:46.380 align:middle line:84%
And that, for me, is
always the bottom line.

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:51.000 align:middle line:84%
It also allows the foot to then
do normal human foot things,

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:52.650 align:middle line:90%
like grab the ground.

00:25:52.650 --> 00:25:57.140 align:middle line:84%
And in that process, get its
exercise and its therapy.

00:25:57.140 --> 00:25:59.920 align:middle line:84%
You know, we're self
exercising, self-healing.

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:00.720 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:03.810 align:middle line:84%
And so much happens there with
lymphatic pumping and allowing

00:26:03.810 --> 00:26:09.485 align:middle line:84%
all kinds of fluids to become
mobilized and healthy tissues.

00:26:09.485 --> 00:26:13.410 align:middle line:84%
It's a very important
piece of our humanity

00:26:13.410 --> 00:26:16.910 align:middle line:84%
that gets certainly ruled
out in our culture so much.

00:26:16.910 --> 00:26:20.280 align:middle line:84%
So can you tell us about the
Gokhale Method specifically,

00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:24.420 align:middle line:84%
how it's laid out in the book
and what a reader might be

00:26:24.420 --> 00:26:26.940 align:middle line:90%
able to anticipate and dive in.

00:26:26.940 --> 00:26:33.430 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a step-by-step series
of instructions on how to sit,

00:26:33.430 --> 00:26:36.660 align:middle line:84%
stand, lie down,
bend, walk, lift.

00:26:36.660 --> 00:26:40.770 align:middle line:84%
But it starts with
how I think is

00:26:40.770 --> 00:26:42.810 align:middle line:84%
the safest and
best way to start,

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:45.160 align:middle line:90%
which is elongate the spine.

00:26:45.160 --> 00:26:47.140 align:middle line:90%
So it's like preparing the clay.

00:26:47.140 --> 00:26:49.480 align:middle line:84%
So I like people to begin
with stretch sitting.

00:26:49.480 --> 00:26:50.840 align:middle line:90%
It's easy.

00:26:50.840 --> 00:26:54.300 align:middle line:84%
There's no downside
if it's done gently.

00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:57.270 align:middle line:84%
And then people are encouraged,
because they feel relief

00:26:57.270 --> 00:26:58.200 align:middle line:90%
right away.

00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:01.380 align:middle line:84%
Stretch lying on the back is one
of these other techniques that

00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:05.350 align:middle line:84%
is easy, lot of
bang for the buck,

00:27:05.350 --> 00:27:09.830 align:middle line:84%
and now people feel energized
to invest a little more effort

00:27:09.830 --> 00:27:15.180 align:middle line:84%
in the other techniques,
which take a little bit more

00:27:15.180 --> 00:27:18.810 align:middle line:90%
than a few seconds of learning.

00:27:18.810 --> 00:27:20.740 align:middle line:84%
>> But it teaches
them how to do that?

00:27:20.740 --> 00:27:21.540 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:23.580 align:middle line:90%
It teaches people step-by-step.

00:27:23.580 --> 00:27:25.890 align:middle line:84%
The best way is
always to get a coach.

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:29.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it is a
kinesthetic thing.

00:27:29.070 --> 00:27:31.620 align:middle line:84%
It's like learning to
play golf or tennis.

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:35.010 align:middle line:84%
And having a coach
tell you that, no, you

00:27:35.010 --> 00:27:38.280 align:middle line:84%
don't look like a gorilla,
and take a picture of you

00:27:38.280 --> 00:27:39.270 align:middle line:90%
